{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510410"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:29:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:29:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11545"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11545"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.1,0.16,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42338"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27361"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1528"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2119"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42338"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-month history of painful swelling in the knees and ankles. He also reports previous occasional heel pain and swelling of toes. He is otherwise well, has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is bilateral knee swelling and tenderness. He also has a rash over his elbows and knees (image). Laboratory evaluation shows haemoglobin 140 g/L (135 \u2013 180), white cell count 14 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0 \u2013 11.0), platelet count 440 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L(150 \u2013 450), C-reactive protein 20 mg/L (\u0026lt;5) and RF factor negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following clinical feature would you expect to find in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon","Swan neck deformity","Malar rash","Heliotrope rash","Nail pitting"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe young patient presents with symmetrical polyarthritis, psoriatic plaque, leucocytosis, and elevated CRP. This is suggestive of psoriatic arthritis (PsA) which may present as one of the five patterns: symmetrical polyarthritis, asymmetric oligoarthritis, distal arthritis affecting the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint, arthritis mutilans, and spondyloarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe heel pain and swelling of toes may indicate enthesitis and dactylitis, respectively. which are also findings in PsA. Nail lesions such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epitting\u003C/strong\u003E and onycholysis (separation of the nail from its bed) can be seen in uncomplicated psoriasis or PsA however it is more common in the latter. The severity of nail lesions correlates with the severity of joint and skin disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaynaud\u0027s phenomenon \u003C/strong\u003E(RP) is a sudden onset of cold digits associated with demarcated skin changes of pallor followed by cyanosis then erythema. These colour sequences reflect ischemia followed by hypoxia then reperfusion. Secondary RP may be associated with underlying autoimmune, rheumatic, or hematologic diseases (e.g, scleroderma, Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome, systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), cold agglutinin disease) but it is not associated with psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwan neck deformity \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by flexion of the DIP joint and hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint. It is a feature of advanced rheumatoid arthritis, an unlikely diagnosis in this case due to the presence of typical psoriatic plaque with negative rheumatoid factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalar rash\u003C/strong\u003E, also called a butterfly rash, is characterised by an erythematous flat or raised rash across the bridge of the nose and cheeks. It is associated with SLE and characteristically spares the nasolabial fold. This is an important distinguishing feature from facial erythema in dermatomyositis, which usually involves the nasolabial fold. Of note, mitral stenosis can also cause a chronic malar flush.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eheliotrope rash\u003C/strong\u003E is a red or purplish discolouration of the eyelids. It is pathognomonic for dermatomyositis along with Gottron\u0027s papules and sign. Gottron\u2019s papules are erythematous to violaceous papules over the extensor surfaces of the metacarpophalangeal, PIP, and DIP joints. The Gottron\u2019s sign is an erythematous rash involving these sites and may also be found on the elbows and knees.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nail pitting is associated with development of arthritis in patients with psoriasis","Nail changes, enthesitis and dactylitis are other common features of psoriatic arthritis.","Psoriasis can affect the skin or joints, most commonly presenting as a polyarthritis"],"references":["Stone J. Current diagnosis \u0026 treatment in rheumatology, 4th ed. Columbus, OH: McGraw-Hill Education; 2021.","Lipner SR, Iorizzo M. Clinical pearl: early diagnosis of nail psoriasis and psoriatic arthritis. Cutis. 2017;99(2):138. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28319620/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27361"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14244"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14244"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/30882fb9-8516-424b-b4e1-72c1526eab7d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/30882fb9-8516-424b-b4e1-72c1526eab7d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27361"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-07T16:11:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-07T16:11:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4174"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42338"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"